yggdrasil/Goroutines.content:
Goroutines allow concurrency in Go. Essentially, it tells Go that a function must be run asynchronously.
package main 

import &quot;fmt&quot; 
import &quot;time&quot; 

func main(){ 
	go func(){ // call the goroutine with an anonymous function 
		time.Sleep(time.Second) 
		fmt.Println(&quot;Goroutines are useful??&quot;) 
	}() // This pair of brackets are important as it means that you are calling the function immediately 
	time.Sleep(time.Second * 2) // wait for the go routine to complete 
}
This is fine for now, but often you may have to wait an unknown amount of time. For this, we use channels and blocking.
package main 

import &quot;fmt&quot; 
import &quot;time&quot; 
import &quot;math/random&quot; 

func main(){ 
	stat := make(chan string) 
	go func(stat chan string){ 
		time.Sleep(time.Second * random.Intn(100)) // wait for a random amount of time 
		stat &lt;- &quot;Hi!!&quot; 
	}(stat)
	msg := &lt;- stat // the programme waits here till a message is received 
	fmt.Println(msg) 
}
Channels in Go are often refferred to as pipes. These are, as their names may suggest, storage containers that allow their contents to be transported. In Go, this means transportation between Goroutines.
In out code, the go func(){...}(stat) function call is asynchronous, does its processing, and outputs the result into stat
On the outside, the programme continue till it reaches &lt;- stat which causes the programme to wait till a message arrives.



                  Note




If there is no receiver, the sender wonâ€™t send
This means that the sender also blocks till the receiver is ready
If there is no sender, the receiver wonâ€™t receive
At a time, only one item may be in the channel
The channel is strictly typed



The third point in the above note does have an exception, though: buffered channels. These are channels where you have predefined a holding capacity. For example:
channel := make(chan string, 2) 
Holds 2 strings.
However, this means that it is no longer blocking - unless the capacity is exceeded.



                  Key




A channel pull or push becomes blocking if the channel is full. An unbuffered channel has a capacity of 0 and is thus blocking. Other channels must first exceed capacity.



But what if youâ€™d like to wait for multiple Go routines to finish?
You could type
&lt;- chan1 
&lt;- chan2 
&lt;- chan3 
But thatâ€™s tedious. You can use a WaitGroup!
package main 

import ( 
	&quot;time&quot;
	&quot;sync&quot; 
	&quot;fmt&quot; 
)

main func(){ 
	var wg sync.WaitGroup 
	wg.Add(1) 
	go func(){ 
		defer wg.Done() 
		time.Sleep(time.Second * 2) 
	}() 
	wg.Wait() 
	fmt.Println(&quot;Yey!!&quot;) 
}
The above code initialises a waitgroup tracker, then adds 1 to tell the waitgroup tracker how many goroutines were initialised. From there, a wg.Done method is called once each go routine is done, telling the waitgroup tracker that it has to wait on 1 fewer goroutines. wg.Wait is blocking. Using wg.Add(1) within the goroutine could make it so that we.Wait() is called before wg.Add. Also, passing wg into a function requires &amp;wg as this is not a reference type.
